   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1843_04_15_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <note>1</note>
               <lb/>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trim_IE">Trim</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1843-04-15">
                     15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. Ap<hi rend="superscript">l</hi>. 1843</date>
               </dateline>
               <lb/>
               <salute>D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Sir</salute>
               <note>To be put away</note>
               <lb/>
            </opener>
            <p>I congratulate you on the<lb/>
               success of your Hand bills<lb/>
               of which I see honorable<lb/>
               mention and <hi rend="underline">envious</hi>
               <choice>
                  <orig>men<lb/>
                  tion</orig>
                  <reg>mention</reg>
               </choice> (still more honorable<lb/>
               properly interpreted) in various<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">periodicals</hi> &amp; newspapers -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I can easily <choice>
                  <orig>concieve</orig>
                  <reg>conceive</reg>
               </choice> that<lb/>
               you are too much occupied<lb/>
               with this and other <choice>
                  <orig>specula<lb/>
                  -tions</orig>
                  <reg>speculations</reg>
               </choice> - or that you are<lb/>
               too lazy - to have been able<lb/>
               to answer my note to you<lb/>
               about that little matter of the<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Garryowen_IE">Garryowen</placeName> or the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Snowtown_IE">Snow</placeName> woman</hi>
            </p>
            <p>Ten to one that on <choice>
                  <orig>read<lb/>
                  ing</orig>
                  <reg>reading</reg>
               </choice> this you &amp; your son both<lb/>
               start &amp; recollect that you<lb/>
               have forgotten all about it<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>No matter - I write now<lb/>
               only to tell you that as your<lb/>
               silence consents and proves<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1843_04_15_page02.jpg"/>
               
               to me that you are unconcerned<lb/>
               in this matter I shall take<lb/>
               it for granted that I may<lb/>
               send <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Garryowen_IE">Garryowen</placeName> &amp; Poor<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxB1">Bob</persName> to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChambX1">Chambers</persName> for his<lb/>
               Journal as he much desires<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I shall wait a week <unclear>for</unclear>
               <lb/>
               this date that you may object<lb/>
               if you please - But I hope<lb/>
               you will not <hi rend="underline">please</hi> to object<lb/>
               as I wish to oblige <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChambX1">Chambers</persName>
               <lb/>
               when it can be done so easily<lb/>
               - Therefore if I have no <add>answer</add>
               <lb/>
               from you I shall be<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer> 
               Your pleased &amp;amp; <unclear>obliged</unclear>
               <lb/>
               humble servant<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
            </closer>
            <lb/>
         </div>
